Since activation of neutrophils was observed, after in vivo injection of CAWS, proinflammatory cytokines levels in plasma were measured (Fig. 4
). IL-12 p70 production was increased (Fig. 4d), while levels of IL-1β (b), IL-10 (c), 1L-6 (d) were significantly increased transiently in the first 1–2 h after CAWS injection. Levels of MIP-2 and G-CSF in plasma increased several hours after CAWS injection and were maintained 16 h after CAWS injection (Figs. 4e, f). On the other hand, IL-18, TNF-α, INF-γ, GM-CSF were not detected up to 16 h after CAWS injection (data not shown). Since IL-1β, IL-10, IL-6 was significantly increased, production of these cytokines by casein-induced neutrophils was also measured (Fig. 5
). IL-6 production was enhanced by exposure of neutrophils to CAWS (Fig. 5c), while those of IL-1β and IL-10 were nearly the same in presence or absence of CAWS (Figs. 5a, b).
